1. Local Development (.devcontainer.json & .gitignore)
Your development lifecycle starts inside an isolated environment. Instead of installing Node.js or packages globally on your local computer, the container manages it.

devcontainer.json: This configures VS Code or GitHub Codespaces to build a container matching your exact needs (using the universal:2 image we fixed earlier). When a developer opens this project, the container spins up, reads package.json, and installs your dependencies automatically.

.gitignore: Ensures that temporary development files, your local environment variables, and the heavy node_modules folder are never committed to your public Git history.

2. Dependencies & Logic (package.json & index.html)
This is the core execution layer of your application.

package.json & package-lock.json: Define the exact versions of the libraries your JavaScript code relies on. This ensures that the code running on your computer behaves exactly the same way when deployed to production.

index.html: The entry point of your frontend. It serves the web interface to your users and loads the JavaScript computation logic.

3. Continuous Integration & Security (.github & SECURITY.md)
Every time code leaves a developer's machine and is pushed to GitHub, the automated safeguards kick in.

.github/workflows/codeql.yml: The CodeQL template we finalized runs automatically on every push or pull request to main. It reads your code, maps it against security vulnerabilities, and reports flaws directly into GitHub before they hit production.

SECURITY.md: Provides a clear vulnerability reporting policy for external users or white-hat hackers who discover issues in your live application.

4. Production Deployment (CNAME)
Once the code passes the CodeQL security checks and is merged into main, it goes live.

CNAME: This file contains your custom production domain (e.g., yourdomain.com). When using hosting platforms like GitHub Pages, this file tells the server to route your custom domain directly to your index.html file.

The Integrated Directory Structure
To make sure everything functions flawlessly, your repository folder should be organized exactly like this:

Plaintext
├── .devcontainer/
│   └── devcontainer.json         # Standardizes your container development environment
├── .github/
│   └── workflows/
│       └── codeql.yml            # Automated security analysis pipeline
├── .gitignore                    # Prevents clutter/secrets from being committed
├── CNAME                         # Routes your custom production domain
├── FMS CBC COMPANY PROFILE.pdf   # Static asset (asset documentation)
├── index.html                    # Frontend user interface
├── package.json                  # Project metadata and dependency definitions
├── package-lock.json             # Locked dependency versions for exact production builds
├── README.md                     # Main repository documentation
└── SECURITY.md                   # Instructions for reporting security flaws
Next Step to Go Live
If you are using GitHub Pages to host this:

Push this entire structure to your GitHub repository.

Go to your repository Settings -> Pages.

Under "Build and deployment", set the source to Deploy from a branch and select main.

GitHub will read your index.html to display the site, use your CNAME file to point it to your custom web address, and the .github folder will keep it completely secure.
